              <h3 class="project-details__content-title">Project Overview</h3>
              <p class="project-details__desc-para">
                This project marked my first attempt at designing boss AI systems. I initially planned to prototype the AI using Blueprints and later convert it to C++. However, due to the tight one month jam deadline and the absence of a more experienced Unreal Engine programmer I was collaborating with, I ended up completing the entire AI logic in Blueprints.
              </p>
			  <h3 class="project-details__content-title">Challenges and Takeaways</h3>
              <p class="project-details__desc-para">
                 From the beginning of development, I started building the boss AI logic using Blueprints, following a structure similar to a state machine—manually handling transitions and behavior using Gates, Branches, and Sequences. At the time, I wasn’t aware that Unreal Engine had built-in systems like State Trees and Behavior Trees specifically designed for this purpose. I only discovered their existence near the end of the jam, which was too late to integrate them properly. In hindsight, using those tools would have made the logic much cleaner, modular, and easier to scale. You can view an example of my custom Blueprint logic <a href="https://blueprintue.com/blueprint/5gnb_szi/" target="_blank">here</a>.
              </p>
            </div>
			<h3 class="project-details__content-title">My Role and Boss Design Breakdown</h3>

<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  As the lead gameplay programmer, I designed and implemented the behavior systems for all three bosses in Clocktergeist. Each boss introduced unique mechanics, patterns, and environmental challenges to push the player's movement, positioning, and reaction timing.
</p>
<h3 class="project-details__desc-para"><strong>Pendulum Boss</strong></h3>
<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  The first boss features a giant swinging pendulum with two alternating phases:
</p>
<ul class="project-details__desc-list">
  <li>
    <strong>Phase 1:</strong> The pendulum swings back and forth like a chainsaw, periodically spawning slow-moving homing orbs that follow the player. These orbs can be countered with a wrench (one-hit) or the nail gun (multiple shots).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Phase 2:</strong> The pendulum stops swinging, drops to the ground, and begins rotating around a central axis. During this phase, the player must grapple over the pendulum while dodging orbs.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Second Health Phase:</strong> Once the boss hits 50% health, it adds a new flame hazard—parallel lines of fire spawn on either side of the player after a brief ground warning. This forces the player to stay mobile and alert.
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 class="project-details__desc-para"><strong>Bell Boss</strong></h4>
<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  The second boss introduces vertical and timing-based challenges through bell shockwaves:
</p>
<ul class="project-details__desc-list">
  <li>
    Bell swings release radial shockwaves that propagate from the center outward, either low or high. The player must either stay grounded or grapple upward to dodge them.
  </li>
  <li>
    Clock-hand minions spawn throughout the fight, requiring quick responses. They can be eliminated with one wrench hit or multiple nail gun shots.
  </li>
  <li>
    The arena also punishes static positioning. If the player remains still too long, an electric charge targets their location after a short warning, forcing constant movement.
  </li>
</ul>
<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  The player's goal is to survive these layered threats and deal damage to the tolling bell to bring the boss down.
</p>

<h1 class="project-details__desc-para"><strong>Clocktower Lady (Final Boss)</strong></h1>
<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  The final boss takes place on a two-tiered arena:
</p>
<ul class="project-details__desc-list">
  <li>
    The top layer is small but safe and allows free movement. The lower layer is sandy, heavily reducing the player's speed and making it much harder to dodge.
  </li>
  <li>
    The boss teleports between four fixed points (NW, NE, SE, SW) and uses two main attacks in her first phase:
    <ul>
      <li>A sudden gear throw with no warning.</li>
      <li>A charged orb attack where five orbs spawn sequentially around her and then launch at the player.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    At ~60% health, she summons a ghostly version of the Pendulum Boss (in its second phase), complete with orb projectiles and fire spawns. This enemy cannot be damaged and must be avoided while continuing to focus on the lady.
  </li>
  <li>
    At ~30% health, the pendulum disappears and a ghost version of the Bell Boss appears, sending out waves that can knock the player down to the sandy lower tier.
  </li>
  <li>
    The lady also upgrades her orb attack, spawning three consecutive sets of five orbs each. This effect required a unique implementation.
  </li>
</ul>

<p class="project-details__desc-para">
  To execute the rotating orb pattern, I couldn't rely on standard rotation mechanics. Instead, I used custom math based on parametric equations:
</p>

<pre class="project-details__desc-code">
  (u + r * cos(t), v + r * sin(t))
</pre>

